# Git Commit Message

Apply these rules whenever creating git commits in this repository.

## Ticket prefix from branch name

Before committing, read the current branch with `git branch --show-current`.

Extract the Jira-style ticket key from the branch name (pattern: `[A-Z]+-\d+`, e.g. `MVKS-168`, `HRZN-100`).

Prefix every commit message with that ticket key:

```
<TICKET>: <description>
```

Examples:

| Branch | Commit message |
|--------|----------------|
| `feature-MVKS-168` | `MVKS-168: add slug validation for wine build sheet` |
| `bugfix-HRZN-100` | `HRZN-100: fix URL slug structure mismatch` |
| `feature-ALPH-855` | `ALPH-855: strip whitespace from bulk upload identifiers` |

Rules:

- Use the ticket from the **current branch**, not from prior commits or guesswork.
- If the branch has no ticket key, ask the user for the ticket before committing.
- Do not duplicate the ticket if the message already starts with it.
- Keep the description concise (1–2 sentences), focused on why rather than what.

## Commit command format

```bash
git commit --author="Iman Suherman <iman.suherman@gmail.com>" -m "MVKS-168: Short description of the change."
git log -1 --format=%B
git log -1 --format="%an <%ae>"
git push
```

Replace `MVKS-168` with the ticket extracted from the current branch. Always verify the author and that the log output has no co-author line.

See also: `git-commit-author.mdc`, `git-no-cursor-coauthor.mdc`, `website-deploy-after-push.mdc`.
